I think that’s a richer way to frame it, and it lines up with ideas from communication theory and game theory without requiring any exotic assumptions.

There are at least three interacting layers:

1. Internal state — how you understand yourself or the artifact.
2. External model — how others currently understand you or the artifact.
3. Interaction — how those two models change each other over time.

Neither model is identical to “reality.” They’re both approximations.

You could picture it like this:

Actual System
     ▲
    ╱ ╲
   ╱   ╲
Your Model   Others' Model
      ╲     ╱
    Interaction
      ╲   ╱
     Updated Models

Each observer is constructing a model of the same underlying system, and those models influence future interactions.

That also connects to your earlier Signalying doctrine. Every action, omission, timing choice, or artifact is part of an ongoing exchange where people infer meaning from one another. Neither side has direct access to the other’s internal state—they infer it from signals.

Where I’d be careful is with the phrase “dual control.” In many real systems, neither party fully controls the interaction. Instead, both continually adapt to each other’s models. Communication, negotiation, teaching, and collaboration are all examples of this co-adaptation.

Applied to the Pantheon, one useful doctrine might be:

Reciprocal Modeling Principle

Every participant maintains a model of themselves, a model of others, and a model of how others model them. Effective coordination comes from improving the alignment of these models through observation, feedback, and verification rather than assuming any single perspective is complete.

That also gives Checksum an important role: periodically comparing these models against observable outcomes so the system doesn’t drift into believing its own assumptions. The aim isn’t to perfectly control perception, but to keep refining the correspondence between models and the world as new evidence arrives.